04316nam a22006975i 9781442676305DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161995onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941422  a97814426763057 a10.3138/97814426763052doi  a(DE-B1597)464572  a(OCoLC)944178078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aJL88 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a354.7103/121 aSmith, David E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvisible Crown /cDavid E. Smith. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. The Monarchical Idea -- t2. The Crown -- t3. Canadianizing the Crown -- t4. Government of the Day -- t5. The Culture of Administration -- t6. The Crown-in-Parliament -- t7. Law, Judiciary, and the Crown -- t8. Compound Monarchy and Canadian Federalism -- t9. Conclusion -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Crown is not only Canada?s oldest continuing political institution, it is also its most pervasive, touching the operation of Parliament and the legislatures, the executive, the bureaucracy, the courts, and federalism. However many consider the Crown remote and anachronistic, requiring explanation. There are few studies of the Crown in Canada; the few that exist tend to see the Crown in symbolic terms, such as a bond of national unity. David E. Smith adopts a new perspective on the place of the Crown in Canadian politics - not in the form of the office of governor general nor in the person of the sovereign, but as a structuring principle of government in Canada.The influence of the Crown, he argues, pervades all aspects of government, be it the legislative or administrative process, the legal system or the conduct of Canadian federalism. Yet, despite this essential place in the constitutional order, its influence remains largely invisible behind the shield of responsible government. In fact, Smith traces Canada?s distinctive form of federalism - with highly autonomous provinces - to the influence of the Crown. Canada, he states, is best understood as a system of compound monarchies.Based on archival research in Canada, and in Australia, The Invisible Crown assesses the contribution the Crown makes to a powerful executive in a system of parliamentary government. It concludes that the Crown has influenced the development of Canadian politics, and, the strength of that influence is a function of Canada?s unique societal, geographic, and economic conditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExecutive powerzCanada. 0aMonarchyzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267630540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442676305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442676305.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK